In this episode, we formally enter Kubernetes Security.
Until now, you learned how Kubernetes works.
From this episode onward, we focus on how Kubernetes stays secure — and how attackers actually break it.


Topics Covered-
What is SIG‑Security (Why It Exists) ?

Kubernetes security is governed by a dedicated working group called SIG‑Security
(Special Interest Group – Security).

1. SIG‑Security Defines:

Threat models for Kubernetes
Secure design principles
Admission control behavior
Secrets and credential security
Supply‑chain security direction
CVE handling and mitigations


Key Point:
SIG‑Security defines how Kubernetes should fail safely, not just how it runs.

Interview‑Grade Line:

Kubernetes security controls are aligned with SIG‑Security threat models and layered defense principles.


2️. Kubernetes Security Is NOT One Feature
A very common beginner mistake:
❌ Security = RBAC
❌ Security = NetworkPolicy
❌ Security = PodSecurity only
This is incorrect.

Kubernetes security is layered, not tool‑based.


3️. The 4 Kubernetes Security Layers (Core Concept)
Kubernetes security is designed as four defensive layers.
Infrastructure → Cluster → Workload → Supply Chain

Attackers always target the weakest layer.

🔐 Layer 1 — Infrastructure Security
(Foundation: OS + Hardware)
Security starts below Kubernetes.
If infrastructure is compromised, Kubernetes security becomes irrelevant.

Includes:

Physical DC or cloud host security 
OS hardening (RHEL CIS, kernel tuning)
Secure boot & firmware trust
HIPS and HIDS on Nodes
Disk encryption
Node isolation
NTP & time integrity
Network segmentation
Central Logging  

BFSI Reality:
RBI and PSU bank audits usually start here:

OS CIS compliance
Root access traceability
Patch and vulnerability management


Rule:
No hardened OS → No compliant Kubernetes cluster


🔐 Layer 2 — Cluster Security
(Control Plane + Core APIs)
This layer protects Kubernetes itself.
If Cluster Security Fails:

Unauthorized API access
Privilege escalation via RBAC
Token theft
etcd data compromise

Controls in This Layer:

API Server authentication & authorization
RBAC (who can do what)
Admission Controllers
etcd encryption at rest
Audit logging
Certificate lifecycle (kube‑ca)


Important:
Cluster security protects Kubernetes, not application logic.


🔐 Layer 3 — Workload Security
(Pods, Containers, Runtime)
This is where applications actually run.
Pods must always be treated as untrusted by default.

Common Threats:

Privileged containers
Container escape attempts
Lateral movement inside cluster
Namespace takeovers
Secret leakage

Controls:

Pod Security Standards
SecurityContext hardening
Linux capabilities drop
Network Policies
Runtime security (Falco / eBPF)
Read‑only root filesystem


Security Principle:
Even trusted apps must run with minimum privilege.


🔐 Layer 4 — Supply Chain Security
(Images, CI/CD, Artifacts)
This is the most modern and most ignored layer.
Most Kubernetes breaches start before deployment.
Real‑World Attack Sources:

Malicious base images
Image typosquatting
Compromised CI pipelines
Unsigned or tampered images

Controls:

Trusted private registries
Image vulnerability scanning
Image signing and verification
Provenance tracking
Admission‑time enforcement


Banking Truth:
If you trust every image, your cluster is already compromised.


4️⃣ Why All 4 Layers Matter Together
Security fails when any one layer is weak.
Attackers do not break everything —
they break the weakest layer first.
✅ Effective Kubernetes security requires:
Infrastructure + Cluster + Workload + Supply Chain


5️⃣ Validating Cluster Security Footprint (Baseline)
Before adding tools, we must validate the baseline.
High‑Level Validation Questions:

Is API server authentication enforced?
Is anonymous access disabled?
Is etcd encrypted at rest?
Are audit logs enabled?
Are namespaces isolated?
Are defaults permissive or restrictive?


Mindset:
Validation before hardening prevents false security.


